            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> Ok let's try it.\r\n> \r\n> > Not directly, but it also doesn't indicate that it's not allowed.\r\n> \r\n> Just in general, in any case of ambiguity, we must always favour the lowest-common-denominator for the widest support. If a server doesn't have to support a zero-rootdir config with multiple documents, then we should never assume/require it. I guess this is exactly why lspconfig had `single_file_support`.\r\n> \r\n> However, since we had this behaviour before it should be safe enough to revert to it for now.\r\n\r\n\r\n> Hmm, what do we do about these cases https://github.com/search?q=repo%3Aneovim%2Fnvim-lspconfig+%22single_file_support+%3D+false%22&type=code ?\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nAfaik single file support in lspconfig is about whether a server supports `root_dir = nil` at all. It's not about if a server can handle multiple files being opened with `root_dir = nil`.\r\n\r\nSo those with `single_file_support = false` need a workspace folder - and afaik the behavior of lspconfig is that it doesn't start/attach a client at all if there isn't one.\r\n\r\nThat's different from what the reuse client default is about.\r\n\r\n*Edit*:\r\n\r\nIf we wanted to mirror that, `lsp.enable` would need a `requires_workspace: boolean` or something like that. So far we didn't have that concept because `lsp.start` didn't need it as it was kinda implicit - if the user calls it, they'd need to know that the server can handle whatever root_dir/workspaceFolder configuration the user provided. \r\n",
